<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n54119k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54119k">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54119k"> 119(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> we who / live under heaven, we in / flowery kingdom, we of the / middle kingdom, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54119k"><li>FW 110.04f </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n54119k">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n54119k">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54119k">MS BL 47476a-205</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:433 <a name="ed11" href="../../FF/fdra/eda.htm#ed11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed11.htm#n54119k">Draft: I.5&sect;1.11</a>/4.11</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Theirs was not <i>a</i> country but <i>the</i> country: their beloved spot of mud was the world. They occasionaly referred to themseves as <mark>&lsquo;we who live under Heaven&rsquo; or &lsquo;We of the Middle Kingdom&rsquo; or &lsquo;We of the Flowery Kingdom&rsquo;</mark>, not as a means of geographical identification but as a general term showing their collective unity. <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 34</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
